{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"49921cd2-6e7c-4f56-b09e-3f2fd2a0e455","content":"On .NET 8 the SDK's `dotnet test` doesn't natively speak MTP, so you run the test project directly and swap to MTP switches:\n\n```bash\ndotnet run --project <TestProject> -- \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --collect-coverage \\\n  --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump \\\n  --hangdump-timeout 5min\n```\n\n**Switch mapping:**\n\n| VSTest | MTP |\n|---|---|\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--collect-coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `--hangdump` |\n| `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump-timeout 5min` |\n| `--filter` | `--filter` (unchanged) |\n\n**Required NuGet packages** in the test project:\n\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump\" />\n```\n\n> **Note:** Starting with .NET SDK **9.0.200+**, `dotnet test` gains native MTP support, so you could go back to `dotnet test` without `dotnet run --project`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d34496a9-bd55-48e5-831f-f5094f4c4d37","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) on .NET 8. Let me provide the equivalent command.\n\nKey differences between VSTest and MTP:\n- `--filter` → `--filter` (same)\n- `--logger trx` → `--report-trx`\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--collect-coverage` with coverage settings\n- `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump`\n- `--blame-hang` → `--hangdump`\n- `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` → `--hangdump-timeout 5m`\n\n\n- With MTP, you can still use `dotnet test` with the `--` separator to pass arguments directly to the test executable, or run the test app directly, though the exact approach depends on your .NET SDK version and whether you're using the VSTestBridge extension.\n\nFor .NET 8 specifically, the most straightforward path is running the test project directly with `dotnet run`, then mapping the standard test arguments to their MTP equivalents—things like `--filter` staying the same, but `--logger trx` becoming `--report-trx` with the appropriate extension, and `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` mapping to `--collect-coverage`. I need to clarify the .NET 8 situation here—MTP integration is actually a .NET 9 feature with the SDK 9.0.200+, so on .NET 8 you'd need to either build and run the test executable directly or use `dotnet run` to invoke it with MTP arguments. Let me give them the right approach for their setup.","outputTokens":1488,"requestId":"702E:2211CA:DBA7F66:F1E6222:69F2A847"},"id":"90efea4b-b260-4e17-a6e5-20d0c071be7c","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:54:56.133Z","parentId":"b5557611-34e7-4cd8-9c16-b00a0781747a"}
